        <h2>Scientific Publications by Dr. Lavian</h2>

        <p>Dr. Lavian has co-authored several scientific publications, journal articles, and peer-reviewed papers on topics in telecommunications, network communications, Internet protocols, and mobile wireless technologies. These publications cover various topics and provide valuable insights into the latest research and developments in these fields.</p>

        <p>Some examples of the topics covered in Dr. Lavian&rsquo;s scientific publications include:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Six models that characterize modern approaches to advanced research</li>
          <li>Potential legal issues surrounding combinations of separate software applications in the age of open source software and the General Public License</li>
          <li>Achieving an open, programmable paradigm for application-driven network control via a novel network plane</li>
          <li>Innovating a grid-computing paradigm that fully harnesses the available communication infrastructure</li>
          <li>Wireless LAN (WLAN)</li>
          <li>TCP/IP suite, TCP, UDP and IP</li>
          <li>Ethernet and the 802.3 standard</li>
          <li>Network protocols and software applications&mdash;including the data link, network, and transport layers (L2, L3, L4) plus data center network architecture</li>
          <li>LANs, WANs, VPNs and routing protocols&mdash;from RIP, BGP, MPLS, and OSPF to multicast, DNS, QoS, switching and packet switching</li>
          <li>PSTN as well as IP telephony, VoIP, SIP, RTP, SS7</li>
          <li>Streaming media, SMS and instant messaging/chat via video and audio</li>
          <li>Wi-Fi and the 802.11 (a/b/g/n/ac) standard</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Dr. Lavian&rsquo;s scientific publications provide valuable insights into the latest research and developments in telecommunications, network communications, Internet protocols, and mobile wireless technologies. These publications are a testament to his expertise in these areas and his contributions to networking and communications.</p>

        <h4>Communications Architecture &ndash; Grid Computing</h4>
        <h5>Tal Lavian, Scholar&rsquo;s Press 2013 ISBN 978-3-639-51098-0.</h5>

        <h4>R&amp;D Models for Advanced Development</h4>
        <h5>Understanding Six Models of Advanced R&amp;D</h5>
        <p>Dr. Tal Lavian offers insightful and decisive expertise as a telecommunications expert witness and network communications expert witness.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/RD_Models_for_Advanced_Development_and_Corporate_Research.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Secure Lightpath Creation Across Heterogeneous Domains</h4>
        <h5>Feature Topic: Optical Control Planes for Grid Networks: Opportunities, Challenges and the Vision.</h5>
        <p>We realize an open, programmable paradigm for application-driven network control by way of a novel network plane &ndash; the &ldquo;service plane&rdquo; &ndash; layered above legacy networks. The service plane bridges domains, establishes trust, and exposes control to credited users/applications while preventing unauthorized access and resource theft. The authentication, authorization, and accounting subsystem and the dynamic resource allocation controller are two novel technologies presented in this work that make this possible.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/AbstractPlus-Applications-Drive-Secure-Lightpath-Creation-Across-Heterogeneous-Domains.pdf">pdf</a> | <a href="/files/publications/IEEE-COMMAG-05-00302-Applications-Drive-Secure-Lightpath-Creation-across-Heterogeneous-Domains.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Data communications architecture grid computing</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T. Lambda Data Grid: A Communications Architecture for Data-Intensive Grid Computing. Doctoral Dissertation, University of California, Berkeley. Fall 2006.</h5>
        <p>In this thesis, we present a communication architecture in support of grid computing and data-intensive applications. The purpose of this research is to extend the grid computing paradigm so it fully harnesses the available communication infrastructure.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/Lavian-PhD-Dissertation-Lambda-Data-Grid-Communications-Architecture-in-Support-of-Grid-Computing.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Information Switching Networks</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T.; Mambretti J.; He E.; Deploying and Using Control and Management Planes for Networking Research, WITSP, 2005.</h5>
        <p>Information Technology is continually being used to create new services and new capabilities for research and education communities throughout the world. Many of these services and capabilities are in the process of being enhanced or transformed through the deployment and use of advanced optical networks.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/Information-switching-Networks-2005002479.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Grid Network Services, Draft-ggf-ghpn-netservices-1.0</h4>
        <h5>George Clapp, Tiziana Ferrari, Doan B. Hoang, Gigi Karmous-Edwards, Tal Lavian, Mark J. Leese, Paul Mealor, Inder Monga, Volker Sander, Franco Travostino, Global Grid Forum(GGF).</h5>
        <p>A network service is further labeled as a Grid network service whenever the service has roles and/or interfaces that are deemed to be specific to a grid infrastructure. The three dominant foci of this GHPN effort are a) the relationship between network services and the known elements of grid infrastructure, b) the functional characterization of each grid network service, and c) the interplay among grid network services.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/draft-ggf-ghpn-netservices-1.0.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Grid Computing &ndash; Network Operators</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T. Impact of Grid Computing on Network Operators and HW Vendors, IEEE Hot Interconnects 12, Stanford, CA., August 2005.</h5>
        <p>Grid computing has a significant impact on network architecture, resource management, and the relationship between service providers and equipment vendors in the telecommunications industry.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/Grid-Panel-Impact-of-Grid-Computing-on-Network-Operators-and-HW-Vendors.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Project DRAC: Creating an applications-aware network</h4>
        <h5>Travostino F.; Daspit P.; Leon-Garcia A.; Bhatt J.; Lavian T.; Nortel Technical Journal.</h5>
        <p>Project DRAC is an industry-leading project that enables applications to dynamically orchestrate network resources, creating an applications-aware network that can adapt to changing requirements in real-time.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/Nortel-Journal-Project-DRAC-Creating-an-applications-aware-network.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Data intensive Grid service &ndash;Optical networks</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T.; Hoang D.B.; Mambretti J.; Figueira S.; Naiksatam S.; Bhatt J.; Daspit P.; Monga I.; Durairaj R.; Merrill S.; Cohen H.; Travostino F; DWDM-RAM: A Data Intensive Service Architecture Enabled by Next Generation Dynamic Optical Networks. CCGRID, 2004.</h5>
        <p>Data intensive applications in sciences, engineering, and medicine are progressively growing in their need for high bandwidth and high burst capacity. We present an architecture for a platform that provides data intensive services on demand to application users over dynamic optical networks.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/AbstractPlus-DWDM-RAM-A-Data-Intensive-Grid-Service-Architecture-Enabled-by-Dynamic-Optical-Networks.pdf">pdf</a> | <a href="/files/publications/DWDM-RAM-A-Data-Intensive-Grid-Service-Architecture-Enabled-by-Dynamic-Optical-Networks.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>quality of control loop on programmable routers</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T.; Wang P.; Travostino F.; Mambretti J.; Lange D.; Hoang D. B.; Subramanian R.; Implementation of a Quality of Service Feedback Control Loop on Programmable Routers, IEEE ICON, Singapore, November, 2004.</h5>
        <p>Achieving effective quality of service in networks requires the integration of monitoring, analysis, and control mechanisms. This paper presents a feedback control loop implementation on programmable routers that enables dynamic QoS management.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/AbstractPlus-Implementation-of-a-Quality-of-Service-Feedback-Control-Loop-on-Programmable-Routers.pdf">pdf</a> | <a href="/files/publications/ICON-2004-Implementation-of-a-Quality-of-Service-Feedback-Control-Loop-on-Programmable-Routers.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Large-Scale Grid Data Networks</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T.; Hoang D.B.; Mambretti J.; Figueira S.; Naiksatam S.; Kaushil N.; Monga I.; Durairaj R.; Cutrell D.; Merrill S.; Cohen H.; Daspit P.; Travostino F; GridNets 2004, San Jose, CA., October 2004.</h5>
        <p>Data intensive Grid applications often deal with multiple terabytes and even petabytes of data. For them to be effectively deployed over distances, it is crucial that Grid infrastructures learn how to best exploit high-performance networks (such as agile optical networks).</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/Gridnets-V101-A-Platform-for-Large-Scale-Grid-Data-Service-on-Dynamic-High-Performance-Networks.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Optical Network ggf-ghpn-opticalnets standard</h4>
        <h5>Gigi Karmous-Edwards, Tal Lavian, Jim Recvlosky, Matt Zekauskas, Franco Travostino, Victor Reijs, GFD-I.036, GGF, March 2004.</h5>
        <p>This document defines the Grid Forum standard for optical network services, establishing the framework for how grid computing environments interact with and manage optical network resources.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/GHPN-GFD-I036-Optical-Network-Service-Interface-draft-ggf-ghpn-opticalnets-1.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Enabling Grid Services with Dynamic Optical Networks</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T.; Mambretti J.; Hoang D.; Cutrell D.; Merrill S.; IEEE/ACM, Globecom, 2004.</h5>
        <p>Grid services require dynamic provisioning of network resources to support the burst-capacity demands of data-intensive applications. This work presents an architecture that enables grid services through dynamic control of optical network resources.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/AbstractPlus-DWDM-RAM-Enabling-Grid-Services-with-Dynamic-Optical-Networks.pdf">pdf</a> | <a href="/files/publications/DWDM-RAM-Enabling-Grid-Services-with-Dynamic-Optical-Networks.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Programmable Internet Service Architecture</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T.; Wang P.; Travostino F.; Subramanian S.; Hoang D. B.; Sethaput V.; An Extensible Programmable Commercial-grade Platform for Internet Service Architecture, IEEE Transactions on Systems, Man and Cybernetics, 2004.</h5>
        <p>This paper presents an extensible and programmable platform designed for deploying Internet services on commercial-grade networking equipment, enabling dynamic service creation and management.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/AbstractPlus-An-extensible-programmable-commercial-grade-platform-for-internet-service-architecture.pdf">pdf</a> | <a href="/files/publications/IEEE-Transactions-on-Systems-An-extensible-programmable-commercial-grade-platform-for-internet-service-architecture.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Edge device multi-unicasting for video streaming</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T.; Hoang D. B.; Travostino F.; Edge device multi-unicasting for video streaming, IEEE ICT 2003, Tahiti, February 2003.</h5>
        <p>This paper proposes an edge-device based multi-unicasting approach for efficient video streaming, enabling scalable content distribution without the complexity of traditional multicast protocols.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/AbstractPlus-Edge-device-multi-unicasting-for-video-streaming.pdf">pdf</a> | <a href="/files/publications/IEEE-ICT-2003-Edge-device-multi-unicasting-for-video-streaming.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Service Composition Across Multiple Providers</h4>
        <h5>Raman B.; Agarwal S.; Chen Y.; Caesar M.; Cui W.; Lai K.; Lavian T.; Machiraju S.; Mao Z. M.; Porter G.; Roscoe T.; Subramanian L.; Suzuki T.; Zhuang S.; Joseph A. D.; Katz Y.H.; Stoica I.; Proceedings of the First International Conference on Pervasive Computing. ACM Pervasive 2002, pp. 1 &ndash; 14.</h5>
        <p>Services are capabilities that enable applications and are crucial to pervasive computing in next-generation networks. Service Composition is the construction of complex services from primitive ones, thus allowing the rapid and flexible creation of new services.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/p368-raman.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Active Flow Network Forwarding Engines</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T.; Wang P.; Travostino F.; Subramanian S.; Hoang D. B.; Sethaput V.; Enabling Active Flow Manipulation in Silicon-based Network Forwarding Engines, DANCE 2002, San Jose, May 2002.</h5>
        <p>This work describes the design and implementation of active flow manipulation capabilities within silicon-based network forwarding engines, enabling intelligent packet processing at line speed.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/AbstractPlus-Enabling-Active-Flow-Manipulation-in-Silicon-based-Network-Forwarding-Engines.pdf">pdf</a> | <a href="/files/publications/Enabling-Active-Flow-Manipulation-in-Silicon-based-Network-Forwarding-Engines.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Active Network Services Content Gateways</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T.; Wang P.; Travostino F.; Subramanian S.; Hoang D. B.; Sethaput V.; Practical Active Network Services within Content-aware Gateways, DARPA Active Networks Conference and Exposition (DANCE), San Jose, CA, May 2002.</h5>
        <p>This paper presents a practical approach to deploying active network services within content-aware gateways, enabling dynamic service delivery in production network environments.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/AbstractPlus-Practical-Active-Network-Services-Within-Content-aware-Gateways.pdf">pdf</a> | <a href="/files/publications/Practical-Active-Network-Services-Within-Content-aware-Gateways.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Active Networks on A Programmable Network Platform</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T.; Wang P.; Travostino F.; Subramanian S.; Hoang D. B.; Sethaput V.; Active Networking on a Programmable Network Platform, IEEE OPENARCH, Anchorage, AK, April 2002.</h5>
        <p>This work demonstrates how active networking concepts can be deployed on commercial-grade programmable network platforms, bridging the gap between research prototypes and production deployments.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/AbstractPlus-Active-Networking-On-A-Programmable-Network-Platform.pdf">pdf</a> | <a href="/files/publications/Open-Arch-2001-Active-Networking-On-A-Programmable-Network-Platform.pdf">pdf</a></p>

        <h4>Active networking &ndash; programmable networking platform</h4>
        <h5>Lavian T.; Hoang D. B.; Wang P.; Travostino F.; Subramanian S.; Sethaput V.; Active Networking Capability in a Programmable Networking Platform, Workshop on Active Middleware Services (AMS), Proceedings of Ninth International Symposium on High Performance Distributed Computing, IEEE, August 2001.</h5>
        <p>Active Networking (AN) is a network architecture concept based on the principle that routers and switches in the network are not only able to forward packets but also to perform computations on the data flowing through them.</p>
        <p><a href="/files/publications/AbstractPlus-Active-Networking-Capability-in-a-Programmable-Networking-Platform.pdf">pdf</a> | <a href="/files/publications/Springer-Active-Networking-Capability-in-a-Programmable-Networking-Platform.pdf">pdf</a></p>

